  title      = {Optimizing Roadside Slope Protection: Herbaceous Plant Densities and Components Impact on Erosion Control},
  year       = {2024},
  month      = aug,
  number     = {4925953},
  pages      = {36},
  abstract   = {Road construction has produced a large number of exposed slopes, and herbaceous plants restoration has become the mainstream way of roadside slope ecological restoration. However, information regarding how the erosion processes and control efficiency on roadside slop differ as functions of herbaceous plants densities and components is lacking. The Bothriochloa ischcemum (Linn.). Keng (BI) and the  Artemisia vestita Wall. ex Bess (AG) were planted to investigate the effect of aboveground part, BSCs and plant root system on runoff and sediment yield under different planting densities. In total, 24 steel tanks were planted, and two tanks were used as bare soil controls. The artificial simulated rainfalls (60 mm h-1) were conducted on a 15° slope, and the runoff generation and sediment yield were measured. The results showed that the herbaceous plants would effectively reduce the runoff and sediment yield by 4.47\% to 60.89\%, 64.47\% to 93.31\% for BI, and 2.90\% to 45.05\%, 63.95\% to 90.05\% for AG, respectively. The contributions on runoff and sediment yield were increased with increasing of planting densities as power functions both BI and AG. When the planting density was 25 plant m-2 , the reduction of sediment yield slightly increases. Generally, the high contribution on runoff was found in aboveground, and it was 1.05 to 2.54 times than that of BSCs and plant root system. However, the high value contribution on sediment yield was found in plant root system, and it was 4.73 and 12.62, 37.19 and 1.80 times than that of aboveground part and BSCs in BI and AG, respectively. In total, the contribution on runoff and sediment yield of BI were 1.52 and 1.01 times than that of AG. Finally, in roadside slop protection process, we recommend planting a density of 25 plant m-2 herbaceous plants with stolon and a fibrous root system.},
